<dl id="n12215h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12215h">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12215h"> 215(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">C</font> we enjoy in plural / <font face="wake">D</font> suffer in sing <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12215h"><li>FW 488.16-17 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n12215h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n12215h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n12215h">MS BL 47484a-43</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:178 <a name="rAd4" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rAd4">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rA/rAd4.htm#n12215h">Draft: III&sect;3A.4</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">L&apos;imagination qui fait les h&eacute;ros travaille sur des donn&eacute;es limit&eacute;es. Quand les hommes &eacute;prouvent le besoin de transposer dans un mode relev&eacute; ce qu&apos;ils font ou souffrent, croient faire ou croient souffrir au pluriel et au collectif, les m&ecirc;mes verbes, mis au singulier, ont pour sujet le h&eacute;ros. <br><font color="green">[The imagination that creates heroes works on very limited material. When people feel the need to transpose that which they do or suffer, what they think they make or believe <mark>they suffer in an elevated mode, in the plural and in the collective, the same verbs have, in the singular, the hero as a subject</mark>.]</font> <small> Stefan Czarnowski, <a name="SCSP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SCSP"><cite title="source">Le culte des h&eacute;ros et ses conditions sociale: saint Patrick, h&eacute;ros nationale de l'Irlande</cite></a> (1919) XC</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
